# Windows script hosts require CRLF. cmd.exe does not fail loudly on an LF-only
# batch file — it half-executes it, dropping leading characters from lines
# ("netstat" -> "tstat", "REM" -> "EM") until commands stop being recognised.
# start-all.cmd hit exactly that: the "is the bridge already listening?" guard
# silently evaluated as failed, so the script logged "starting bridge" and then
# ran none of the rest, leaving no bridge started and no error anywhere.
#
# core.autocrlf=true converts on checkout, but it only applies to files git
# actually writes — anything created or rewritten in place by an editor or a
# tool keeps whatever endings that tool used. These rules make it explicit and
# checkout-independent. regression.mjs asserts it too, because a silently
# half-executed watchdog is the worst thing in this repo to get wrong.
*.cmd text eol=crlf
*.bat text eol=crlf
*.vbs text eol=crlf
*.ps1 text eol=crlf
